    {
      "id": "lmClPmyo_d0yg7C5S1krS",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 568.91796875,
      "y": 1367.4609375,
      "width": 2017.9374310560524,
      "height": 875,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2A",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1901301506,
      "version": 227,
      "versionNonce": 614243294,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1776702570362,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "==> Here, now we will understand the workflow from external world accessing an instance in an AWS VPC.\n\n        1.  Now we will understand the flow using a drawing above. \n            So there are multiple insights present in the VPC, so the flow will start from an external world. \n\n        2. So, from an external world, it will have the public IP, so the first that request will come to the internet gateway. \n            The internet gateway will have the public IP from where the subnet will have the same IP range, \n            and from there it will reach to the load balancer. So, in the load balancer, the IP will be translated from a private IP to the public IP. \n\n        3. In the load balancer, there will be a route table that we'll be having in the load balancer so that, \n            to which target group the request wants to access, to which instance it wants to access, that information will be available in the route table.\n\n        4. Based on that route table, it will reach to the instance before reaching to the other instance, so they will be having a security group. \n\n        5. So for every instance, there will be a security group like a firewall who can access that instance. What is the subnet it should access that instance or any port it is allowed? \n            All the port information and the subnet information will be present in the security group. \n\n        6. A simple brief about how the flow will travel from the external world to an internal private instance hosted in the AWS VPC:\n            \n        From the external world, it will come to the first Internet gateway here, from public IP to private IP. The IP will be NATED. And from there, the request will be forwarded to the LB. \n\n        In LB, there will be load balancing. So, in that load balancing, it will also have a route table. Here, we can see there are multiple instances available. \n\n        To which instance it has to be routed traffic so that information will be available in the route table. \n\n        From the route table, it will go to the respective instance, and before reaching the instance, for every instance, there will be one security group.\n\n        And in the security group, it will have the information about which port is allowed and what IP addresses are allowed to access that instance. \n        That information will be present in that security group.\n\n        SNAT : S-Nat is called as a stateless NAT. So when it is used, if the return traffic is going via LB, then the private IP will be NATed to the public IP in the load balancing level. \n        So then it is called as a stateless NAT.   \n\n        If the return traffic is going via NAT, it means a gateway. In a gateway, the private IP will be converted into a public IP. To mask the private IP is because it is not a good habit to expose the private IP to the external world. \n        So, in that scenario, NAT will be used (Network Address Transition). ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "==> Here, now we will understand the workflow from external world accessing an instance in an AWS VPC.\n\n        1.  Now we will understand the flow using a drawing above. \n            So there are multiple insights present in the VPC, so the flow will start from an external world. \n\n        2. So, from an external world, it will have the public IP, so the first that request will come to the internet gateway. \n            The internet gateway will have the public IP from where the subnet will have the same IP range, \n            and from there it will reach to the load balancer. So, in the load balancer, the IP will be translated from a private IP to the public IP. \n\n        3. In the load balancer, there will be a route table that we'll be having in the load balancer so that, \n            to which target group the request wants to access, to which instance it wants to access, that information will be available in the route table.\n\n        4. Based on that route table, it will reach to the instance before reaching to the other instance, so they will be having a security group. \n\n        5. So for every instance, there will be a security group like a firewall who can access that instance. What is the subnet it should access that instance or any port it is allowed? \n            All the port information and the subnet information will be present in the security group. \n\n        6. A simple brief about how the flow will travel from the external world to an internal private instance hosted in the AWS VPC:\n            \n        From the external world, it will come to the first Internet gateway here, from public IP to private IP. The IP will be NATED. And from there, the request will be forwarded to the LB. \n\n        In LB, there will be load balancing. So, in that load balancing, it will also have a route table. Here, we can see there are multiple instances available. \n\n        To which instance it has to be routed traffic so that information will be available in the route table. \n\n        From the route table, it will go to the respective instance, and before reaching the instance, for every instance, there will be one security group.\n\n        And in the security group, it will have the information about which port is allowed and what IP addresses are allowed to access that instance. \n        That information will be present in that security group.\n\n        SNAT : S-Nat is called as a stateless NAT. So when it is used, if the return traffic is going via LB, then the private IP will be NATed to the public IP in the load balancing level. \n        So then it is called as a stateless NAT.   \n\n        If the return traffic is going via NAT, it means a gateway. In a gateway, the private IP will be converted into a public IP. To mask the private IP is because it is not a good habit to expose the private IP to the external world. \n        So, in that scenario, NAT will be used (Network Address Transition). ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
