      "seed": 1716113893,
      "version": 146,
      "versionNonce": 1662716101,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1776791673488,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Security Group SG :",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Security Group SG :",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "6BKoCgAnFjtQQLbV6uDZU",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 794.68359375,
      "y": 2424.91015625,
      "width": 1443.4465248063207,
      "height": 225,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2H",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1986931179,
      "version": 211,
      "versionNonce": 369835403,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1776791936042,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "==> Security group will be handled at the instance level. Which means in an instance the application will be running \nso for that application any of the inbond access and out bound access can be mentioned in the security group. \n\n==> So for example if you are running a Python application in that instance which is running on port 8000, \nif I want to access that application from the external world, that port 8080 will be opened in the security group. \n\n==> Then we can access this application at a total cost from an external model. This SG security group will be handled by the application team at instance level \n\n==> Security group can handle the incoming and outgoing traffic at IP level and port level. ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "==> Security group will be handled at the instance level. Which means in an instance the application will be running \nso for that application any of the inbond access and out bound access can be mentioned in the security group. \n\n==> So for example if you are running a Python application in that instance which is running on port 8000, \nif I want to access that application from the external world, that port 8080 will be opened in the security group. \n\n==> Then we can access this application at a total cost from an external model. This SG security group will be handled by the application team at instance level \n\n==> Security group can handle the incoming and outgoing traffic at IP level and port level. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "twSEJCIm0bDd0A7rHwoh2",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1010.9728359244764,
      "y": 2712.9140625,
      "width": 467.96825332194567,
      "height": 35,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2I",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2029459723,
      "version": 577,
      "versionNonce": 2045617061,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1776792223407,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Network Access Control List NACLs :",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Network Access Control List NACLs :",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "iFSKIuYAtU5gDKvu9O4ah",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 806.765625,
      "y": 2821.71484375,
      "width": 1286.1068031266332,
      "height": 250,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2J",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 352945035,
      "version": 227,
      "versionNonce": 440061285,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1776792226098,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "==> The NACL will have high priority over the security group for an instance.\n\n==>  If the 8000 port allowed in instance level at security group, but that 8000 port is denied in NACL, then the incoming traffic will be denied.\n\n==> NACL mostly will be implemented at the subnet level. Whereas security group will be implemented at the instance level \n\n==> When we create a VPC, by default AWS is going to create an internet gateway and a route table to that particular VPC. \n\n==> By default, all the inbound access or inbound traffic will be denied to that particular VPC by AWS. \n        We need to explicitly allow that traffic based on the subnet or based on the port to that particular VPC.  ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "==> The NACL will have high priority over the security group for an instance.\n\n==>  If the 8000 port allowed in instance level at security group, but that 8000 port is denied in NACL, then the incoming traffic will be denied.\n\n==> NACL mostly will be implemented at the subnet level. Whereas security group will be implemented at the instance level \n\n==> When we create a VPC, by default AWS is going to create an internet gateway and a route table to that particular VPC. \n\n==> By default, all the inbound access or inbound traffic will be denied to that particular VPC by AWS. \n        We need to explicitly allow that traffic based on the subnet or based on the port to that particular VPC.  ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
