    {
      "id": "6Ds-fSEup6X8YNGUlmljG",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 870.30859375,
      "y": 4530.8087158203125,
      "width": 1762.6807537078857,
      "height": 850,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2f",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1513483236,
      "version": 501,
      "versionNonce": 1399256028,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777396515610,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "==> So the diagram is just to illustrate how public and private subnets work in a company even though in Zoho. \n\n==> First we need to create a VPC of a subnet in 10.0.0.1/16. \n\n        One note here: in AWS when we create a VPC, it will be created in two availability zones, 1a and 1b. \n    In both availability zones the subnet will be the same and the instance in that VPC will have the IP addresses in the same subnet which we have created above, 10.0.0.1/24. \n\n==> Now I am going to tell step by step how we can create the above architecture. \n\n1. First create a VPC of a subnet 10.0.0.1/16. It will have public and private IPs. \n\n2. Then create two EC2 instances in one A and another instance in one B for the high availability. \n    Note this instance will be having the private IPs, which means it cannot be accessible from the public environment, that is, the external world. \n\n3. So now we can create a landing server from where we can access these two EC2 instances. \n    From that landing the landing server will have the public IP and it is hosted in the private subnets but it will have a public IP. We can enable the public IP for that instance.\n\n4. Now we have created an EC2 instance and landing servers. Now we can create a load balancer so the load balancer will distribute the load based on the traffic to the target groups. \n\n5. Before creating a load balancer, create a target group \n\n6. After creating a target group in both instances, we can run a Python application which is running at port number 8000. \n\n7. And after creating the target group, we can create a load balancer and we can attach the target group to that load balancer. \n    Note that in the load balancer the load balancer will be listening on port 80 and that port should be enabled in the security groups of the load balancer.  \n    \n    Another note here: after attaching the target groups to the load balancer, we need to select the option \"Include as pending\"; then only it is going to attach the target groups to the load balancer. \n\n\n8. The subnet of a load balancer should be public so that it should be able to be accessed over the public internet. Keep this in mind: it should be hosted on the public network not private. \n    If you are having a private network then we cannot access the load balancer. \n\n9. Now we have an EC2 instance, load balancer, and landing. After implementing all this, take the A record DNS value from the load balancer. \n    You can check in the browser; it can be accessed. ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "==> So the diagram is just to illustrate how public and private subnets work in a company even though in Zoho. \n\n==> First we need to create a VPC of a subnet in 10.0.0.1/16. \n\n        One note here: in AWS when we create a VPC, it will be created in two availability zones, 1a and 1b. \n    In both availability zones the subnet will be the same and the instance in that VPC will have the IP addresses in the same subnet which we have created above, 10.0.0.1/24. \n\n==> Now I am going to tell step by step how we can create the above architecture. \n\n1. First create a VPC of a subnet 10.0.0.1/16. It will have public and private IPs. \n\n2. Then create two EC2 instances in one A and another instance in one B for the high availability. \n    Note this instance will be having the private IPs, which means it cannot be accessible from the public environment, that is, the external world. \n\n3. So now we can create a landing server from where we can access these two EC2 instances. \n    From that landing the landing server will have the public IP and it is hosted in the private subnets but it will have a public IP. We can enable the public IP for that instance.\n\n4. Now we have created an EC2 instance and landing servers. Now we can create a load balancer so the load balancer will distribute the load based on the traffic to the target groups. \n\n5. Before creating a load balancer, create a target group \n\n6. After creating a target group in both instances, we can run a Python application which is running at port number 8000. \n\n7. And after creating the target group, we can create a load balancer and we can attach the target group to that load balancer. \n    Note that in the load balancer the load balancer will be listening on port 80 and that port should be enabled in the security groups of the load balancer.  \n    \n    Another note here: after attaching the target groups to the load balancer, we need to select the option \"Include as pending\"; then only it is going to attach the target groups to the load balancer. \n\n\n8. The subnet of a load balancer should be public so that it should be able to be accessed over the public internet. Keep this in mind: it should be hosted on the public network not private. \n    If you are having a private network then we cannot access the load balancer. \n\n9. Now we have an EC2 instance, load balancer, and landing. After implementing all this, take the A record DNS value from the load balancer. \n    You can check in the browser; it can be accessed. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "da0tDVqIgV-qy1tTh7Lmn",
