    },
    {
      "id": "z8L9BxOU5IeBT8SFWGPkt",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 919.4609375,
      "y": 5532.74609375,
      "width": 1570.9607830047607,
      "height": 650,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2h",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1681503580,
      "version": 401,
      "versionNonce": 1758382052,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777396933697,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "==> So in here I am explaining briefly about the simple storage service that is S3 in AWS. For the practice purpose we can use the code cloud platform; \n        it is way better for the practice purpose. \n\n\n==> Also AWS S3 bucket documentation is available in this AWS folder. \n\n==> We can save anything in the AWS S3 bucket; it can be any format: logs, pics, videos, messages. Anything; there is no restriction to save in the S3 bucket. \n\n==> Why it is popular means because of its five unique features:\n- High availability\n- More security\n- Scalable\n- Cost-effective\n\n==>  We have S3 classes and nothing but there are different types of classes available here. Based on the classes which we select for the storage purpose, \n        the cost will be different for the different storage purposes so \n\n==> For better understanding we can take our DC example. For NVMe read and write will be faster and for HDD/SSD and hardware, read and write operations will be slower. \n\n==> So based on this only they have classified into different classes for the fast read and write. There is a different class and the charges of that class will be different. \n        Based on our need of what kind of objects we are storing in S3 we can select based on our requirement for the class that will be applicable. \n\n==> As we know for any storage purpose there will be access management lock, same as how you are blocking the server and tag options are also available. \n        There are also a bunch of things available which we can learn in kodekloud practice sessions. \n\n==> For more info use aws pdf from kodekloud and also use practise session.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "==> So in here I am explaining briefly about the simple storage service that is S3 in AWS. For the practice purpose we can use the code cloud platform; \n        it is way better for the practice purpose. \n\n\n==> Also AWS S3 bucket documentation is available in this AWS folder. \n\n==> We can save anything in the AWS S3 bucket; it can be any format: logs, pics, videos, messages. Anything; there is no restriction to save in the S3 bucket. \n\n==> Why it is popular means because of its five unique features:\n- High availability\n- More security\n- Scalable\n- Cost-effective\n\n==>  We have S3 classes and nothing but there are different types of classes available here. Based on the classes which we select for the storage purpose, \n        the cost will be different for the different storage purposes so \n\n==> For better understanding we can take our DC example. For NVMe read and write will be faster and for HDD/SSD and hardware, read and write operations will be slower. \n\n==> So based on this only they have classified into different classes for the fast read and write. There is a different class and the charges of that class will be different. \n        Based on our need of what kind of objects we are storing in S3 we can select based on our requirement for the class that will be applicable. \n\n==> As we know for any storage purpose there will be access management lock, same as how you are blocking the server and tag options are also available. \n        There are also a bunch of things available which we can learn in kodekloud practice sessions. \n\n==> For more info use aws pdf from kodekloud and also use practise session.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "kXj-ZhlRcmMbIPINlHBBT",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1382.234375,
      "y": 6264.03125,
      "width": 390.3376626968384,
      "height": 35,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
