    },
    {
      "id": "W_0Thv9uT8o7ZIdf19g8o",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 978.1015625,
      "y": 6427.5,
      "width": 1863.2431802749634,
      "height": 550,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2j",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1599800717,
      "version": 101,
      "versionNonce": 235690957,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1778174709919,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "==> CloudFormation template is nothing but it is a process of provisioning the S3, EC2 instance, and RDS (that is, database), which is a help of templates. \n\n==> We will write a template in the form of a JSON or YAML file in which we will mention all the resources and properties related \n        to S3, EC2, and RDS to create provisioning and automate the AWS resources with the help of a template. \n\n==> So we will create a template and that template will upload into the cloud formation stack so when we upload that into the stack it is going to analyze that file or a template \n        and it is going to create a resource for us quick. It's very fast. \n\n==> The  template, which we are writing, should be declarative and versioned in nature. \n        What is this? Version means it will have a change log so we can see the version. So what is the previous version, or if you have made any changes to the template and we have updated in that template,\n         we can see the versions. That's what should be there in the template . What we are declaring in the template should be created in the resources, and in a short form, \n        what we see what we write in the template should be equal to what we see in the AWS resources. \n\n==> The main important attribute in the template is'resource'. Under'resource', we will write more properties related to the resources. \n\n==> The template which we are going to upload in the AWS Cloud Formation, we call it  Stack. \n\n==> In cloud formation, there are metadata, stacks, and parameters also available. So that is not a more important thing. So better we should know these things are available. \n\n==> We have a drift functionality or a future available in AWS cloud formation. So when we have written a template and against to the template, \nif any user has made any changes in the resource level, then we can see that in the drift detect and drift changes. So when we identify that, then we can able to remove that permission to that particular user. \nThis will help us to track the changes to our services which are not being in the template. ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "==> CloudFormation template is nothing but it is a process of provisioning the S3, EC2 instance, and RDS (that is, database), which is a help of templates. \n\n==> We will write a template in the form of a JSON or YAML file in which we will mention all the resources and properties related \n        to S3, EC2, and RDS to create provisioning and automate the AWS resources with the help of a template. \n\n==> So we will create a template and that template will upload into the cloud formation stack so when we upload that into the stack it is going to analyze that file or a template \n        and it is going to create a resource for us quick. It's very fast. \n\n==> The  template, which we are writing, should be declarative and versioned in nature. \n        What is this? Version means it will have a change log so we can see the version. So what is the previous version, or if you have made any changes to the template and we have updated in that template,\n         we can see the versions. That's what should be there in the template . What we are declaring in the template should be created in the resources, and in a short form, \n        what we see what we write in the template should be equal to what we see in the AWS resources. \n\n==> The main important attribute in the template is'resource'. Under'resource', we will write more properties related to the resources. \n\n==> The template which we are going to upload in the AWS Cloud Formation, we call it  Stack. \n\n==> In cloud formation, there are metadata, stacks, and parameters also available. So that is not a more important thing. So better we should know these things are available. \n\n==> We have a drift functionality or a future available in AWS cloud formation. So when we have written a template and against to the template, \nif any user has made any changes in the resource level, then we can see that in the drift detect and drift changes. So when we identify that, then we can able to remove that permission to that particular user. \nThis will help us to track the changes to our services which are not being in the template. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
