    {
      "id": "KWizid4G7acfda_l9ctbE",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1072.78125,
      "y": 7228.851806640625,
      "width": 1405.7775785177946,
      "height": 150,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2l",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1119231111,
      "version": 29,
      "versionNonce": 138273575,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1778520356142,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "==> So the basic information about AWS CodePipeline is that it is used to integrate the CI/CD pipeline. \n\n==> So what does a CI/CD pipeline mean in a short way? It is used to deliver continuous integration and continuous delivery without breaking the pipelines. \n\n==> So here I am going to explain how the architecture of a CI/CD pipeline, not in the AWS environment, outside the AWS environment, \n            how the CI/CD pipeline will be implemented. ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "==> So the basic information about AWS CodePipeline is that it is used to integrate the CI/CD pipeline. \n\n==> So what does a CI/CD pipeline mean in a short way? It is used to deliver continuous integration and continuous delivery without breaking the pipelines. \n\n==> So here I am going to explain how the architecture of a CI/CD pipeline, not in the AWS environment, outside the AWS environment, \n            how the CI/CD pipeline will be implemented. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
