    {
      "id": "R7NweouyxZw0tDmQQyGzV",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1950.14453125,
      "y": 7652.422119140625,
      "width": 1110.478140041232,
      "height": 50,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b30",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1026185639,
      "version": 51,
      "versionNonce": 1081882057,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1778520581277,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "The JAR and WAR file will be uploaded to the EC2 instance. In the EC2 instance we will have an Engine Access servlets or \nWeb App application servers where this JAR or WAR file will be uploaded and it will be used. ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "The JAR and WAR file will be uploaded to the EC2 instance. In the EC2 instance we will have an Engine Access servlets or \nWeb App application servers where this JAR or WAR file will be uploaded and it will be used. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "FyoYHTx04dunaNfSWZpXe",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1122.2852934383004,
      "y": 7846.311977067564,
      "width": 1718.797231838107,
      "height": 350,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b31",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1268236679,
      "version": 73,
      "versionNonce": 1263727008,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1779125581243,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "==> So here if you see, we are using different open sources at gate. We are using Jenkins. We are using the EC2 and for the build purpose we will be using Maven for Java-based applications. \n\n==>So here we are using the different open source. What AWS has done here is, instead of using the different open source tools, we can use the AWS CodeCommit service, \n        which is going to handle all the actions, all the operations performed by these tools. \n\n==> To complete these operations, which are done by the open source tools, AWS has services like CodePipeline, CodeBuild, and CodeDeploy. \n\n==> By the help of these tools we can implement a complete CI/CD pipeline with AWS CodeCommit. \n\nNote : Note we should be familiar with the git actions and code commit is not that popular in the industry because it has a lot of restrictions and it is having disadvantages like:\n- less integrations with the other services (third-party services)\n- we cannot integrate it\n- very strict restrictions are also available there\nDue to these disadvantages the companies will not use it much with the AWS Code Commit service.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "==> So here if you see, we are using different open sources at gate. We are using Jenkins. We are using the EC2 and for the build purpose we will be using Maven for Java-based applications. \n\n==>So here we are using the different open source. What AWS has done here is, instead of using the different open source tools, we can use the AWS CodeCommit service, \n        which is going to handle all the actions, all the operations performed by these tools. \n\n==> To complete these operations, which are done by the open source tools, AWS has services like CodePipeline, CodeBuild, and CodeDeploy. \n\n==> By the help of these tools we can implement a complete CI/CD pipeline with AWS CodeCommit. \n\nNote : Note we should be familiar with the git actions and code commit is not that popular in the industry because it has a lot of restrictions and it is having disadvantages like:\n- less integrations with the other services (third-party services)\n- we cannot integrate it\n- very strict restrictions are also available there\nDue to these disadvantages the companies will not use it much with the AWS Code Commit service.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "HxEtxI4KeMiJ0HsQ_iHTx",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1365.125462558444,
      "y": 8286.886538065022,
      "width": 355.599203273654,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b32",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1573362791,
      "version": 152,
      "versionNonce": 1452243367,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1778520810191,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Learn GIT to get more hands on actions",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Learn GIT to get more hands on actions",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "nAqyZPWuNKL70NH1nQvZV",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1186.983199496382,
      "y": 8424.581157390403,
      "width": 1487.6421734392643,
      "height": 700,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b33",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1280404625,
      "version": 319,
      "versionNonce": 2060281407,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1778692521549,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "==> Git is a version-controlled tool which helps us to maintain track of the source code or any repo. \n\n==> We can go back and forth to the old versions if we want to change or if you're facing any issues in the current versions. We can go back to the previous versions. \n        Git helps us go back and forth between versions. \n\n==> Whatever the code we are writing in our local machine after installing the gate, it is called a local repo, which we are developing in our local machine. \n\n==> Let's understand what is the difference between a git and GitHub. \n\n==> So Git is nothing but we install Git on our local machine. \n        We write the code on our local machine and we try to integrate the code with other team mates in the remote repo, which is hosted on GitHub. \n\n==>In simple words the code which we are writing in our local machine will be developed and managed with the help of Git. \n        All the team members' source code will be integrated at one place, which is called GitHub.\n\n==> Local repo versus remote repo \n\n==>Local repo equals git, which will develop source code on our local machine. \n\n==> GitHub refers to the remote repo where all the team members' source code will be integrated at one place. \n\n==>  Some imp git cmds are given below for day to day use\n\n        git init , git status , git add , git push,\n\n       To undo last push are jump to previous commit id\n\n        git reset --hard id , git status",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "==> Git is a version-controlled tool which helps us to maintain track of the source code or any repo. \n\n==> We can go back and forth to the old versions if we want to change or if you're facing any issues in the current versions. We can go back to the previous versions. \n        Git helps us go back and forth between versions. \n\n==> Whatever the code we are writing in our local machine after installing the gate, it is called a local repo, which we are developing in our local machine. \n\n==> Let's understand what is the difference between a git and GitHub. \n\n==> So Git is nothing but we install Git on our local machine. \n        We write the code on our local machine and we try to integrate the code with other team mates in the remote repo, which is hosted on GitHub. \n\n==>In simple words the code which we are writing in our local machine will be developed and managed with the help of Git. \n        All the team members' source code will be integrated at one place, which is called GitHub.\n\n==> Local repo versus remote repo \n\n==>Local repo equals git, which will develop source code on our local machine. \n\n==> GitHub refers to the remote repo where all the team members' source code will be integrated at one place. \n\n==>  Some imp git cmds are given below for day to day use\n\n        git init , git status , git add , git push,\n\n       To undo last push are jump to previous commit id\n\n        git reset --hard id , git status",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
